WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.120
Hi, my name is Andrew Bray, and I'm an Associate Teaching Professor in Statistics at UC Berkeley.

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:14.720
I'd like to tell you my top three reasons why you should take the Introduction to Quarto

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:17.440
Workshop at PositConf.

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:20.080
Number one, feel the flexibility.

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:23.639
One of the things I love about Quarto is how flexible it is.

00:00:23.639 --> 00:00:25.240
Authoring a document always feels the same.

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:30.879
I'm typing into a simple text file, but when I go to render it, I could make a PDF file

00:00:30.879 --> 00:00:34.919
or Word document or an HTML file or a slide presentation.

00:00:34.919 --> 00:00:41.340
What's more, if there's code in that document, it could be R code or Shiny or Python or Julia.

00:00:41.340 --> 00:00:44.360
In this workshop, you'll get to feel that flexibility.

00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:49.020
At the end of the day, you'll produce a broad range of polished documents, and you'll emerge

00:00:49.020 --> 00:00:52.720
with a big picture view of everything that's possible with Quarto.

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:55.639
Reason number two, a guide through the docs.

00:00:55.639 --> 00:00:59.959
If you've started tinkering around with Quarto, you've probably discovered that there's extensive

00:00:59.959 --> 00:01:03.040
documentation available at quarto.org.

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:06.300
But if you're just getting started, this can be pretty overwhelming.

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:11.400
In this workshop, you're getting a curated guide through the vast functionality of Quarto.

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:15.919
In the morning, we'll start off with a single static document, and then we'll add functionality

00:01:15.919 --> 00:01:19.360
bit by bit until we have something quite sophisticated.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:24.440
In the afternoon, we'll shift our focus to putting together a beautiful slide presentation.

00:01:24.440 --> 00:01:27.000
Reason number three, live coding.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:31.559
Something that many of the workshops at Positive Comp share is the practice of live coding.

00:01:31.559 --> 00:01:35.760
This means that in addition to using slides, I'll be projecting my RStudio session so you

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:39.000
can see me code up a Quarto document live.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.320
This is helpful because in addition to getting to see the syntax, you're also getting to

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:45.680
see the workflow of authoring a Quarto document.

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:50.000
And when errors pop up, because they will pop up, you'll get to see somebody else's

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.040
approach to getting unstuck.

00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:55.599
So if you're ready to dive into everything you can do with Quarto, please join us at

00:01:55.599 --> 00:01:57.139
the workshop in Chicago.

00:01:57.139 --> 00:01:57.879
We hope to see you there.

